[ctns_demo flashcard]

[ctns_make id='LF-HLineS']

    [ctns_front]
Horizontal Line
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
If $$y$$ is a constant, then the graph of the linear function is a <strong>horizontal line</strong>; and, the slope of this line is 0.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='LF-VLineS']

    [ctns_front]
Vertical Line
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
If $$x$$ is a constant, then the graph of the linear function is a <strong>vertical line</strong>; and, the slope of this line is <em>infinite</em>.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='LF-PaLineS']

    [ctns_front]
Two lines are parallel if ...
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;']
Two lines are parallel if they have the same slope.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='LF-PeLineS']

    [ctns_front]
Two lines are perpendicular if ...
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;']
Two lines are perpendicular if their slopes are negative reciprocals.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='LF-InterceptS']

    [ctns_front]
X-Intercept and Y-Intercept<br/>Linear Function
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
The $$y$$-intercept of a function is the value of $$y$$ when $$x=0$$. The $$x$$-intercept of a function is the value of $$x$$ when $$y=0$$. 
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='LF-XInterceptS']

    [ctns_front]
X-Intercept<br/>Linear Function
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
The $$x$$-intercept of a function is the value of $$x$$ when $$y=0$$. 
    [/ctns_back]
    
    [ctns_frontspeak]
The x-intercept -- linear function.
    [/ctns_frontspeak]

    [ctns_backspeak]
The x-intercept of a function is the value of x when y equals 0.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='LF-YInterceptS']

    [ctns_front]
Y-Intercept<br/>Linear Function
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
The $$y$$-intercept of a function is the value of $$y$$ when $$x=0$$. 
    [/ctns_back]
    
    [ctns_frontspeak]
The y-intercept -- linear function.
    [/ctns_frontspeak]

    [ctns_backspeak]
The y-intercept of a function is the value of y when x equals 0.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='LF-SlopeS']

    [ctns_front]
Slope<br/>Linear Function
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:90%;font-size:80%;']
The <strong>slope</strong> of a linear function is the ratio
$|\frac{rise}{run}|$
where <em>rise</em> is the vertical distance between two points on the line, and <em>run</em> is the horizontal distance between the same two points.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]




[ctns_make id='LF-SlopeFormulaS']

    [ctns_front]
Slope Formula<br/>Linear Function
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
The <strong>slope</strong> of a linear function is the ratio
$|\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}|$
for two points $$(x_2,y_2)$$ and $$(x_1,y_1)$$ on the graph of the linear function.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='LF-PointSlopeFormS']

    [ctns_front]
Point-Slope Form<br/>Linear Function
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
The <strong>Point-Slope Form</strong> of a linear function is given by the equation,
$|(y-y_1) = m(x-x_1),|$
for all $$x,y \in \mathbb{R}$$ and where $$m$$ is the slope of the line, and $$(x_1, y_1)$$ is a point on the line.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='LF-SlopeInterceptFormS']

    [ctns_front]
Slope-Intercept Form<br/>Linear Function
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
The <strong>Slope-Intercept Form</strong> of a linear function is given by the equation,
$|y = mx + b,|$
for all $$x,y \in \mathbb{R}$$ and where $$m$$ is the slope of the line, and $$b$$ is the $$y$$-intercept.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]





[ctns_make id='LF-GeneralFormS']

    [ctns_front]
General Form<br/>Linear Function
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
The <strong>General Form</strong> of a linear function is given by the equation,
$|Ax+By=C,|$ for all $$x,y \in \mathbb{R}$$ and where $$A$$, $$B$$, and $$C$$ are constants.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]





[ctns_make id='LF-InterceptInterceptFormS']

    [ctns_front]
Slope-Intercept Form<br/>Linear Function
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
The <strong>Intercept-Intercept Form</strong> of a linear function is given by the equation,
$|\frac{x}{A}+\frac{y}{B}=1,|$
for all $$x,y \in \mathbb{R}$$ and where $$A$$ and $$B$$ are constants, $$A,B \neq 0$$.
    [/ctns_back]

[/ctns_make]

[/ctns_demo]